        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/42650",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "What environment are you on, b\/c I cannot reproduce an environment where SCRIPT_NAME is not available.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-10-21T09:19:49.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-10-21T09:19:49.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/47401",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=tfountain",
                        "name": "tfountain",
                        "displayName": "Tim Fountain",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I just hit this problem on one of my boxes. The server is running CentOS 5.5, and also the fcgi version of PHP (not sure if that is relevant - version in this case is 5.2.14). SCRIPT_NAME is set when using PHP normally, but from the command line the variable is null, as in the reporter's case.\r\n\r\nPerhaps a reasonable fix, if $_SERVER['SCRIPT_NAME'] is not set, would be to check if the first argument ends with 'zf.php'.\r\n\r\nLet me know if you need any more environment info or a fix tested.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=tfountain",
                        "name": "tfountain",
                        "displayName": "Tim Fountain",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-07-08T19:51:50.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-07-08T19:51:50.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/47402",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=tfountain",
                        "name": "tfountain",
                        "displayName": "Tim Fountain",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Okay, this was actually a configuration problem on my side. Because of an incorrect path I'd put in, zf.sh was picking up the normal PHP binary instead of the php-cli. So that may well be the cause if anyone else hits this issue. \r\n\r\nPerhaps the fix suggested above could be put in anyway, or if SCRIPT_NAME should always be available to php-cli then an error could be output if it is null, just to help debug problems like this.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=tfountain",
                        "name": "tfountain",
                        "displayName": "Tim Fountain",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-07-08T20:18:46.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-07-08T20:18:46.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
